# 🌐 Networking Basics Notes

## 1. What is a Computer Network?

A computer network is a collection of interconnected devices that communicate and share data and resources with each other. Examples include the Internet, office networks, and home Wi-Fi networks.

### Advantages

* Resource Sharing
* Fast Communication
* Centralized Data Management
* Internet Access
* Improved Collaboration

---

# 2. Types of Networks

### LAN (Local Area Network)

A network covering a small geographical area such as a home, school, or office.

### MAN (Metropolitan Area Network)

A network that covers a city or metropolitan area.

### WAN (Wide Area Network)

A network that spans large geographical areas such as countries or continents. The Internet is the largest WAN.

### PAN (Personal Area Network)

A network connecting personal devices such as smartphones, laptops, and smartwatches.

---

# 3. Network Topologies

### Bus Topology

All devices are connected to a single cable.

### Star Topology

All devices connect to a central switch or hub.

### Ring Topology

Devices are connected in a circular fashion.

### Mesh Topology

Every device is connected to every other device.

### Tree Topology

Combination of Star and Bus topologies.

---

# 4. Networking Devices

## Router

Connects different networks and forwards packets based on IP addresses.

## Switch

Connects devices within the same network and forwards data using MAC addresses.

## Hub

Broadcasts data to all connected devices.

## Access Point (AP)

Provides wireless network connectivity.

## Modem

Connects a network to an Internet Service Provider (ISP).

---

# 5. OSI Model

| Layer | Name         | Function                |
| ----- | ------------ | ----------------------- |
| 7     | Application  | User Interface          |
| 6     | Presentation | Data Formatting         |
| 5     | Session      | Connection Management   |
| 4     | Transport    | Reliable Data Transfer  |
| 3     | Network      | Routing & IP Addressing |
| 2     | Data Link    | MAC Addressing          |
| 1     | Physical     | Cables & Signals        |

**Mnemonic:**
**A**ll **P**eople **S**eem **T**o **N**eed **D**ata **P**rocessing.

---

# 6. TCP/IP Model

| Layer          | Function               |
| -------------- | ---------------------- |
| Application    | User Services          |
| Transport      | TCP & UDP              |
| Internet       | IP Routing             |
| Network Access | Physical Communication |

TCP/IP is the protocol suite used by the Internet.

---

# 7. IP Address

An IP Address uniquely identifies a device on a network.

### Example

```text
192.168.1.10
```

### IPv4

* 32-bit address
* Example: 192.168.1.1

### IPv6

* 128-bit address
* Example:

```text
2001:0db8:85a3::8a2e:0370:7334
```

---

# 8. MAC Address

* Physical Address of a device
* Assigned by manufacturer
* Layer 2 Address

Example:

```text
00:1A:2B:3C:4D:5E
```

---

# 9. Common Protocols

| Protocol | Port  | Purpose                 |
| -------- | ----- | ----------------------- |
| HTTP     | 80    | Web Traffic             |
| HTTPS    | 443   | Secure Web Traffic      |
| FTP      | 21    | File Transfer           |
| SSH      | 22    | Secure Remote Access    |
| DNS      | 53    | Domain Name Resolution  |
| DHCP     | 67/68 | Automatic IP Assignment |
| SMTP     | 25    | Email Sending           |

---

# 10. DNS

DNS (Domain Name System) converts domain names into IP addresses.

Example:

```text
google.com → 142.250.x.x
```

Without DNS, users would need to remember IP addresses.

---

# 11. DHCP

DHCP automatically assigns:

* IP Address
* Subnet Mask
* Default Gateway
* DNS Server

This eliminates manual configuration.

---

# 12. Routing

Routing is the process of forwarding packets between different networks.

### Types

* Static Routing
* Dynamic Routing

Common Dynamic Routing Protocols:

* RIP
* OSPF
* EIGRP

---

# 13. Switching

Switching enables communication between devices within the same network.

Benefits:

* Reduced Collisions
* Better Performance
* Efficient Data Forwarding

---

# 14. Network Security Basics

### Firewall

Filters incoming and outgoing traffic.

### Antivirus

Protects against malware.

### VPN

Creates secure encrypted connections.

### ACL (Access Control List)

Controls network access permissions.

---

# 15. Basic Networking Commands

## Windows

```bash
ipconfig
ping google.com
tracert google.com
nslookup google.com
```

## Linux

```bash
ip addr
ping google.com
traceroute google.com
nslookup google.com
```

---

# 16. Troubleshooting Steps

1. Check Physical Connections
2. Verify IP Address
3. Test Connectivity using Ping
4. Check DNS Resolution
5. Verify Routing
6. Review Firewall Settings

---

